@flexiarg collaboration-coherence/navel-gazing
@title Close the Feedback Loop with an Action; Avoid the Bateson Double-Bind
@keywords feedback, double-bind, criticism, reflection, action, bateson, paragogical-praxis
@audience peer-learning facilitators, project conveners, design-review participants
@tone practical
@style pattern
@references [collaboration-coherence/magical-thinking peeragogy/wrapper peeragogy/discerning-a-pattern]

! conclusion: Reflection and feedback have value only when there is a mechanism for acting on them; the failure mode is feedback channels that absorb critique without consequence — the Bateson double-bind in which the receiver invites criticism while making any effective criticism unwelcome.  The pattern is to close every feedback loop with a named action surface: where critiques go, who decides, what gets changed, what doesn't, and why.  Criticism without an action surface is noise; the *art of paragogical praxis* is to make something useful out of what would otherwise be noise.
  + context: Peer-learning projects, like most reflective communities, accumulate feedback channels (forums, retrospectives, action reviews, comment threads, evaluation surveys).  The failure mode is not too much reflection — it is reflection without a connected action surface.  Contributors offer critique; the critique is heard; the project does not change in response.  Over time, contributors stop bothering, or the most useful critics leave.  The Bateson double-bind makes this concrete: "go ahead, criticise me — but all effective criticism will be unwelcome."  When the implicit reception of criticism is hostile or null, the explicit invitation is destructive.
  + TENSION:
    Axis: reflection ↔ action.
    Real: reflection without action is hollow; action without reflection is reactive.  Both pure modes fail; the question is how the project structures the interface between them.
    Irreducible: a feedback channel cannot simultaneously be a free-flowing reflective space AND a tightly bounded action queue.  The project must decide which channel is which, and how each transitions to the other.
    Active: the pull recurs at every retrospective, every survey, every "tell us how we're doing" prompt — and especially when feedback arrives that the project would prefer not to act on.
  + COMPOSITIONS:
    (1) Action-surface naming: every feedback channel has a recipient (named role or person), a decision cadence (when proposals get adjudicated), and an output convention (how the project records what changed and why).  No channel exists without these three.
    (2) Triage discipline: incoming feedback is sorted into act / defer / decline / out-of-scope, with the rationale recorded.  Decline is a legitimate outcome; absence-of-decision is not.
    (3) Time-boxed reflection: retrospectives have a closing action — at least one named change to be tried before the next retrospective.  Otherwise, the retrospective converts to lament.
    (4) Visible track record: maintain a public log of "changes made in response to feedback" so contributors can see whether their critique landed.  This is the wrapper pattern applied to the feedback loop.
    (5) Name the double-bind: when the project notices itself implicitly punishing useful criticism (defensiveness, no-action, reframing the critic as the problem) — name the dynamic explicitly.  The double-bind dissolves when both parties can see it.
  + CHECK:
    Engaged when: contributors can point to recent changes the project made in response to recent feedback, and contributors who offered feedback know whether it landed or not.  Failing when: critique flows in but nothing flows out; or contributors quietly stop offering useful feedback because the previous round was absorbed without effect.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Open invitation, closed reception: "we welcome criticism!" followed by reflexive defensiveness when criticism actually arrives.  The double-bind in its purest form.
    - Reflection without closure: retrospectives become weekly lament with no commitments; over time they stop being attended.
    - Anonymous absorption: feedback arrives via survey or comment box, gets summarised, and the summary disappears.  No one can say what changed.
    - Critic-as-problem: when criticism is uncomfortable, the focus shifts to "how the critique was delivered" rather than what it said.  The deflection is the symptom.
    - Echo-chamber retrospectives: the same group reviews its own work without external eyes; critique that would be useful is structurally absent.  See also collaboration-coherence/isolation.
